<P>
Federal authorities are conducting preliminary investigations into charges of 
sexual misconduct by at least five members of the House, the Washington Times 
said. It said the investigations by the Justice Department, the Capitol Police 
and at least one House committee involve minors and male prostitutes. Justice 
Department and Capitol Police declined to comment on the paper's report. The 
Washington Times, which did not name those being probed, said the probes also 
extended to current and former congressional staff members. It quoted anonymous 
sources as saying the inquiries were started earlier this year. It said Ohio 
Republican Rep. Donald E. (Buz) Lukens, found guilty last week on charges of 
contributing to the delinquency of a minor, a 16-year-old girl with whom he had 
sexual relations, apparently was not among those being investigated. 
